04963nam a22007815i 9780231544313DE-B159720200826040535.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200826t20172017nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2016041212  a(OCoLC)999361599  a97802315443137 a10.7312/chro179582doi  a(DE-B1597)482784  a(OCoLC)984688680  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aHX806b.P64 2016 4aHX806 7aPHI0400002bisacsh04a321.122300aPolitical Uses of Utopia :bNew Marxist, Anarchist, and Radical Democratic Perspectives /cJames Ingram, S. Chrostowska. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (376 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNew Directions in Critical Theory00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: Utopia and Politics -- t1. The History of Utopia and the Destiny of Its Critique -- t2. Is the Classic Concept of Utopia Ready for the Future? -- t3. Utopia and Natural Illusions -- t4. Marx and Utopia -- t5. General Wish Or General Will? Political Possibility and Collective Capacity from Rousseau Through Marx -- t6. After Utopia, Imagination? -- t7. A Strange Fate for Politics: Jameson’s Dialectic of Utopian Thought -- t8. The Reality of Utopia -- t9. Negativity and Utopia in the Global Justice Movement -- t10. Utopianism and Prefiguration -- t11. The Senses and Uses of Utopia -- t12. Realism, Wishful Thinking, Utopia -- t13. Desire and Shipwreck: Powers of the Vis Utopica -- tUtopia, Alibi -- tContributors -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aUtopia has long been banished from political theory, framed as an impossible—and possibly dangerous—political ideal, a flawed social blueprint, or a thought experiment without any practical import. Even the "realistic utopias" of liberal theory strike many as wishful thinking. Can politics think utopia otherwise? Can utopian thinking contribute to the renewal of politics?In Political Uses of Utopia, an international cast of leading and emerging theorists agree that the uses of utopia for politics are multiple and nuanced and lie somewhere between—or, better yet, beyond—the mainstream caution against it and the conviction that another, better world ought to be possible. Representing a range of perspectives on the grand tradition of Western utopianism, which extends back half a millennium and perhaps as far as Plato, these essays are united in their interest in the relevance of utopianism to specific historical and contemporary political contexts. Featuring contributions from Miguel Abensour, Étienne Balibar, Raymond Geuss, and Jacques Rancière, among others, Political Uses of Utopia reopens the question of whether and how utopianism can inform political thinking and action today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Aug 2020) 0aPolitical sciencexPhilosophy. 0aUtopias - Political aspects. 0aUtopiasxPolitical aspects. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Movements / Critical Theory.2bisacsh1 aChrostowska, S., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aIngram, James, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package 2016-2018z978311066255908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package 2017z978311065472108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook-Package Pilot Project 2017z978311054330840uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/chro1795840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231544313423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780231544313.jpg  a978-3-11-054330-8  CUP eBook-Package Pilot Project 2017b2017  a978-3-11-065472-1  CUP eBook Package 2017b2017  a978-3-11-066255-9  CUP eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  a